{
  "texts": [
    "Starting from an initial configuration Z 0 = Z (1) 0,..., Z (n) 0, we recursively simulate R + 1 child configurations at each time step t, yielding {Z t+1 [r]} r=0,...,R. We designate the branch r = 0 as the main branch {Z t [0]} t=0,...,T -1, from which we extract the conditioning tuplesZ (i) t, {Z (j) t } j∈N (i) tfor all agents i.",
    "The remaining R sibling branches at each t supply the target next states Z (i) t+1, ensuring that each context yields multiple outcomes.",
    "1: repeat 2:t ∼ Uniform(0,..., T -1) 3:Z (i) t, {Z (j) t } j∈N (i) t ← Zt[0] 4: g (i) t = fω(Z (i) t, j∈N (i) t (Z (i) t, Z(j)t)) 5:τ ∼ Uniform(1,..., τmax) 6:τ emb = SinusoidalPositionEmbedding(τ) 7: c (i) t = MLP(Z (i) t) + MLP(g (i) t) + MLP(τ emb) 8: r ∼ Uniform(1,..., R) 9: Z (i) t+1 ← Zt+1[r] 10:ϵ ∼ N (0, I) 11:Optimizers step over all i ∈ A 12:∇ ϕ,ω ||ϵ -ϵ ϕ ( Z(i) t+1 (τ), c(i)t)|| 2 13: until convergence Learning procedure.",
    "Our framework uses these data sets to train the Graph Diffusion Network.",
    "It minimizes the expected denoising loss over the outcomes observed in the ramification data (see Algorithm 1)."
  ]
}